DATA CARD
	
1.	Project Overview
This repository presents KPI-based data quality analysis for historical stock market data of five companies: Amazon, Apple, Microsoft, Nvidia, and Tesla.

Each company is analyzed in a separate Jupyter Notebook using Python. The goal of the project is to evaluate the quality, reliability, and usability of financial data, with a focus on the Close price and overall dataset integrity.




	2.	Source of Data

The data used in this project was collected from Yahoo Finance using the Python library yfinance.

Data Source Description:
	•	Source: Yahoo Finance (public financial data provider)
	•	Access method: yfinance API
	•	Data type: historical stock market data
	•	Frequency: daily (1d)
	•	Format: tabular time-series data

Variables included:
	•	Open
	•	High
	•	Low
	•	Close
	•	Volume
	•	Dividends
	•	Stock Splits

Data Collection Method:
Data was retrieved programmatically using Python with the history() function.

Time Ranges per Company:
	•	Amazon (AMZN): 2009-06-07 – 2010-06-07
	•	Apple (AAPL): 2024-01-01 – 2025-01-01
	•	Microsoft (MSFT): 2023-11-02 – 2024-11-02
	•	Nvidia (NVDA): 2020-06-05 – 2021-06-05
	•	Tesla (TSLA): 2025-02-01 – 2026-02-01

Important Notes:
	•	The data is secondary (not collected manually)
	•	It depends on Yahoo Finance accuracy and availability
	•	Market conditions influence values (volatility, trends, anomalies)





	3.	KPIs

The following KPIs were used to evaluate data quality:

Data Completeness
Measures whether missing values exist in the dataset

Data Latency
Verifies the time range and availability of data

Data Consistency
Checks whether data types and structure are uniform

Error Rate
Includes missing value rate, duplicate rate, and outlier rate (based on IQR method)

Data Accuracy
Checks validity of Close prices, Volume values, and absence of duplicates






